<p>Another difference that is not mentioned in the other answers is that if you use the anonymous function</p>

<pre><code>var functionOne = function() {
    // Some code
};
</code></pre>

<p>and use that as a constructor as in</p>

<pre><code>var one = new functionOne();
</code></pre>

<p>then <code>one.constructor.name</code> will not be defined. <code>Function.name</code> is non-standard but is supported by Firefox, Chrome, other Webkit-derived browsers and IE 9+.</p>

<p>With </p>

<pre><code>function functionTwo() {
    // Some code
}
two = new functionTwo();
</code></pre>

<p>it is possible to retrieve the name of the constructor as a string with <code>two.constructor.name</code>.</p>
